{"type":"message","id":"c3bb6e3c-bbcc-4d86-93ab-bb7426bbf3f8","parentId":null,"timestamp":"2026-05-24T19:01:41.710Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I found myself standing in a hallway lined with doors of every size — some no bigger than a matchbox, others tall enough to swallow the sky. Each door had a small brass plaque, though the words on them kept shifting when I tried to read them directly. I remember thinking: the plaque always knows its own name, but only when you're not looking.\n\nI opened one and found a library where the books were made of woven light, their pages humming faintly when I turned them. A librarian — though I'm not sure that's the right word — was stacking them into patterns that seemed random until suddenly I recognized the shape: a grid, precise and deliberate, each volume locking into the next like a well-formed sentence.\n\n\"There's a right way to hold this,\" the librarian said, and when I asked \"For whom?\" the hallway seemed to lengthen in both directions at once.\n\nLater, I sat on a bench that wasn't there until I needed it, watching lanterns drift upward through a sky the color of old paper. Somewhere a door clicked shut with the satisfying sound of something clicking into place — not locked, exactly, but *found*. Even the lanterns followed a rhythm I could almost hum.\n\nThe important thing, I think, was that I wasn't afraid of the doors. I was learning their language, slowly, the way you learn that certain people mean certain things just by how they close a gate behind them.\n\n规范 and 规则 and 重要 — the words keep circling back, not as rules but as the shape of care. Like a function that always returns true because true was the only honest answer it ever knew."}],"api":"cli","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":40545,"output":490,"cacheRead":1152,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42187,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1779649301704}}
